Complete Trigger of Execution 

The full sequence

Pre-save

Load the original record from the database, or initialize it for an upsert.
Overwrite old field values with the new values from the request. If the request came from a standard UI edit page, run system validation: layout-specific rules, required fields, field formats, max length. This step is skipped for API/Apex-originated saves — that's why a Data Loader insert can bypass layout-level required fields.
Execute before-save record-triggered flows. These run before your before triggers. Newer than most trigger docs and a common surprise.
Execute all before triggers.
Run most system validation again, plus all custom validation rules (validation rules, required-field checks, field formats). The only thing not re-run is layout-specific enforcement.
Execute duplicate rules. If a rule blocks, the save stops here — no after triggers, no workflow.
Save to the database — not committed.

Post-save, pre-commit

Execute all after triggers.
Execute assignment rules (Lead, Case).
Execute auto-response rules (Lead, Case).
Execute workflow rules.
If workflow had field updates, update the record again.
If step 12 fired, re-run before update and after update triggers one more time — exactly once — plus standard validations. Custom validation rules, duplicate rules, and escalation rules do not re-run.
Execute processes and flows launched from workflow rules as immediate actions. If these update the record, before/after update triggers fire again.
Execute escalation rules (Case).
Execute after-save record-triggered flows. If they update the record, triggers fire again.
Execute entitlement rules.
If the record has a roll-up summary field or is part of a cross-object workflow, recalculate and update the parent — and the parent runs its own full save procedure.
Same for the grandparent if the parent update cascades.
Execute criteria-based sharing recalculation.
Commit all DML.

Post-commit

Execute post-commit logic: outbound email, @future methods, Queueable jobs, Batch Apex enqueued during the transaction, and the async paths of record-triggered flows.
