The parts that actually bite

Steps 12–13 — the double fire. A workflow field update re-runs your update triggers. If your handler isn't idempotent or lacks a recursion guard, you get duplicate child records or double-counted roll-ups. This is the #1 reason for static-boolean guards.

Step 18 — parent save procedure. Roll-up summary updates put the parent through the entire order of execution, including its own triggers. A trigger on Opportunity Line Item can silently cascade into Opportunity triggers, then Account triggers, all inside one transaction sharing one set of governor limits.

Steps 2 vs 5 — why formula fields look stale. Formula fields aren't stored; they're computed on read. In a before trigger, reading a formula that depends on a field you just changed in the same trigger gives you the old value. If you need the recomputed value you have to be in after, or requery.

Step 3 — before-save flows beat your trigger. If a flow and a trigger both default the same field, the flow wins the first write and your trigger overwrites it. Worth checking when a value mysteriously isn't what the admin configured.

Steps 7 vs 21 — uncommitted is still visible. Between 7 and 21, SOQL inside the transaction sees the saved values, but nothing is durable. An uncaught exception anywhere through step 20 rolls the whole thing back. This is precisely why callouts are forbidden mid-transaction and why side effects belong in step 22 via Queueable or @future.
