One caveat on your framing

Workflow Rules and Process Builder are both retired for new creation — you can't build new ones, and Salesforce has been migrating existing ones to Flow. They still occupy their steps in the order of execution for legacy automation, so you need to know them for the certification and for maintaining older orgs, but for anything new the relevant steps are 3 (before-save flow) and 16 (after-save flow).

Practical consequence: before-save flows are faster than before triggers for simple field updates — no Apex execution, no separate save. The modern guidance is flow for declarative field updates, Apex triggers for anything requiring complex logic, bulk queries, or callouts.

Given where you are, the recursion guard pattern is the direct follow-on here — steps 12–16 are the reason it exists.
